>>43061017
>It's really up to the writer to establish the differences.
This, right here. The writer &/or artist also has to have some reasonably detailed anatomical knowledge to make "reasonable" decisions about how their anthros are biologically configured. Physically, socially, psychologically. One of the annoying problems in the furry universe is the prevalence of ignorance and the reliance on tropes.

There are a lot of trope-ish assumptions about anthros automatically being vastly superior to humans in strength, size, durability, etc. While it *could* be such (in the creator's universe), it is not necessarily so. If you are designing your anthro off alternate evolution from Earth animals, there are many weaknesses that are ignored that would be inherited.

Canines, have fairly weak legs. Easily broken & crippled. Also true of felines and some others. Evolving to walk upright would compensate somewhat, but not necessarily to the degree that humans evolved. Felines have glass jaws, as do canines to a slightly lesser degree. When they break teeth or lose them due to dental issues, their jaws become even more fragile. This has an effect on survival. Let us also talk about highly carnivorous dietary needs. This can be quite the limiting factor on survival of tribes and species.

Human senses of hearing & smell are diminished in comparison, but our eye sight distinction for color is very superior to most animals. Night puts us at disadvantage, but daylight puts many other animals at disadvantage to us. Human endurance is also legendary on the animal world. We can literally run most animals into the ground. Not by speed, but by marathon. Prey animals can get away in the short term, but when we track and chase them for miles they get exhausted and are vulnerable to us being less exhausted at the final stand.

There are hundreds of such details that SHOULD be taken into consideration, but most artists & writers lack knowledge to do so.

As the humans spread, the humans in very hostile environments formed the first nations, of which were snuffed out fast. Then some human found a cool orange rock and smacked into the shape of a spear, and the first city-state survived. Humans were the first to get metal tools, and this gave them a massive edge, figuratively and literally. Since the other races in tribes barring the elves were more focused on killing each other, the walled cities of mankind became places they would go to and trade, mainly slaves, livestock, and fur in exchange for metal goods, pottery, and food preservatives.
